Kubernetes QoS (Quality of Service) classes determine which Pods are evicted first when a node is under resource pressure (most commonly memory pressure, but also disk/ephemeral-storage pressure). QoS is computed per Pod from the requests/limits across all its containers.
QoS classes (how they’re assigned)

1) Guaranteed (most protected)
A Pod is Guaranteed if every container has both CPU and memory requests and limits, and for each container request == limit (for CPU and for memory).
resources:
  requests: { cpu: "500m", memory: "512Mi" }
  limits:   { cpu: "500m", memory: "512Mi" }

2) Burstable (middle)
A Pod is Burstable if it has some requests/limits set, but it does not meet Guaranteed (e.g., request != limit, or only memory set, etc.).
resources:
  requests: { cpu: "250m", memory: "512Mi" }
  limits:   { cpu: "2",    memory: "2Gi" }

3) BestEffort (least protected)
A Pod is BestEffort if no container in the Pod sets any CPU/memory requests or limits.
resources: {}

Eviction behavior (what happens under pressure)
Kubernetes’ kubelet eviction manager evicts Pods to protect the node. The general eviction preference is:
BestEffort → Burstable → Guaranteed (evict left side first).
Example: Memory pressure eviction on a node
Imagine a node is running these Pods:

Pod A (BestEffort): no requests/limits, currently using 800Mi
Pod B (Burstable): request 512Mi, using 1.5Gi
Pod C (Guaranteed): 512Mi request/limit, using 512Mi

If the node hits a memory eviction threshold:

Pod A is the first eviction candidate (BestEffort).
If still pressured, Pod B is next (Burstable)—and within Burstable, Pods that are using more relative to their requests tend to be stronger candidates.
Pod C (Guaranteed) is evicted last, unless pressure is severe enough that the node can’t recover otherwise.

Important nuance: eviction vs OOMKill

Eviction is kubelet proactively terminating Pods to relieve pressure; it records an eviction reason (e.g., Evicted).
OOMKill happens when a container exceeds its memory limit (or the node kernel runs out of memory). QoS influences who gets killed first at the node level, but a container that exceeds its own limit can be OOMKilled regardless of QoS.

Disk / ephemeral-storage pressure (often overlooked)
QoS also matters for ephemeral-storage pressure if you set ephemeral-storage requests/limits. If you don’t, many workloads behave like “unbounded” from a disk perspective, increasing the chance of evictions when /var/lib/kubelet or imagefs fills up.
Architect-level implications (how to use this)

For critical services, aim for Guaranteed where feasible (especially for memory) to reduce eviction risk.
Use Burstable intentionally for workloads that can tolerate disruption (workers, non-critical APIs) while still giving the scheduler solid signals via requests.
Avoid BestEffort in shared production clusters; it’s the first to go during incidents.
QoS is only one axis: PodPriority, PDBs, and replica counts strongly affect real-world disruption (e.g., a high-priority Burstable pod may outlive a low-priority Guaranteed pod depending on policy/config).


          Eviction and OOMKilled are both “pod died due to resources,” but they originate from different controllers and look different operationally.



