Real Kubernetes scenarios
Scenario A: OOMKilled from a too-low memory limit (common)

A Java service has limits.memory: 512Mi and experiences a traffic spike; heap + off-heap + native threads grow past 512Mi.
The kernel kills the container process immediately; the pod stays on the node and gets restarted (CrashLoopBackOff if repeated).
Symptom pattern: short uptime, Last State: OOMKilled, exit 137; logs may stop mid-line.

Scenario B: Eviction from node memory pressure due to overcommit (common in shared clusters)

Multiple Burstable workloads have low requests but collectively use far more memory than requested, pushing the node below memory.available thresholds.
Kubelet evicts pods to recover, usually starting with BestEffort (e.g., a log shipper with no requests/limits), then Burstable offenders.
Symptom pattern: several pods across namespaces suddenly show Evicted, often clustered on one node; rescheduling happens elsewhere if capacity exists.

Scenario C: Eviction from ephemeral-storage pressure (often overlooked)

A pod writes verbose logs to the container filesystem; node disk (or imagefs) fills up.
Kubelet evicts one or more pods to free ephemeral storage and keep the node functional.
Symptom pattern: Evicted with messages referencing ephemeral-storage, nodefs, or imagefs; repeated if log volume continues.

Scenario D: “OOMKilled” even without a memory limit (node-level kernel OOM)

A BestEffort pod (no limits) plus other workloads push the node into true OOM.
The kernel kills processes based on OOM scoring; a container may show OOMKilled even though it had no limit.
Symptom pattern: node instability, multiple pods impacted, possible node NotReady events; root cause is overall node memory exhaustion, not a single container limit.


How to triage quickly (what to check)

If many pods on one node die with Evicted, look for node pressure (memory/disk) and overcommit (requests too low).
If one pod repeatedly dies with OOMKilled, it’s usually that workload’s memory limit (or a leak) and needs right-sizing/tuning.
Architect fix patterns:

OOMKilled: increase memory limit, reduce peak memory (heap sizing, caching), set request closer to steady-state, consider VPA recommendations.
Evictions: increase requests (reduce overcommit), add capacity/scale nodes, apply LimitRange/Quotas, review noisy-neighbor workloads and eviction thresholds, set ephemeral-storage requests/limits for heavy writers.
